title: #1556 Young Violin Player
description: I created a series of music and dance wirewall sculptures for a show at the Irving Arts Center Performance Hall.  The wall space was massive, two stories tall, lots of natural light and space enough to stand back and view the art - an artist dream. This sculpture is among a series of young kids playing musical instruments.  I visited a school of music where I took most the pictures I worked from.  The instruments and the movement of the lines connecting the kids and the music was magical to me. Wire guided me beyond the drawing to simplify the complex and emphasize the lines the eyes follow to get the feel of the image.

author: James Agard
title: "Hoodoo" Interior Sculpture
description: This sculpture is based on spiraling form not unlike a pretzel. One part of the implied overlapping twist remains unaffected while the other component goes through a significant organic metamorphosis. The title (Hoodoo) refers to the influence the rock spires found throughout the Badlands and Colorado's plateau had on my work. The actual Hoodoo's were inspirational and provided a starting point for my interpretive forms. The varied sized holes allow the background to intersect the work. This piece has a mysterious quality... quite like the Hoodoo rock formations referred to previously. It does feel like a sculpture with magical powers and strength from an unknown source. It's a mysterious sculpture that's as much an experience as it is a sculpture.

The paintings from this series are painted in a gestural and fluid manner, with bright and colourful acrylic paints, they are full of joy.  'Rainbow Flowers' is painted on 250gsm acid free paper, approximately A2 in size.  (58cms x 42cms)  It would work well framed in a simple frame either hung on its own or could be hung alongside other paintings from the collection.  The artwork is signed on the back and has a protective barrier applied to it to help protect it from UV rays and humidity.

author: Yaroslav Sobol
title: IN SEARCH OF TRUTH by Yaroslav Sobol (Original oil painting, The young man went deep into the cave to get answers to his questions.)
description: A young, slender youth stands in a dark cave and holds a torch in his hand. The fire of this torch snatches out of the darkness a barely distinguishable drawing of a bird. This drawing was painted on the wall of the cave many millennia ago. It is not known who made this drawing, but we can definitely tell why. An ancient artist painted this fiery bird to leave us the truth that was known in those distant times. This bird is the truth, which burns lies and deceit with its fire. Unfortunately, sometimes the truth is very difficult to find. Sometimes you have to analyze a lot of information, live for many years to understand what the truth really is. The cave in the picture just symbolizes these years of searching. But the truth is worth the search. Perhaps even a lifetime. And happy is he who, like this young man, has found the truth before he becomes an old man. This means that he still has his whole life, illuminated by the light of truth, ahead of him.

author: Andrey Saharov
title: Tiger Portrait String Art
description: The original string art technique that created this stunning piece involves wrapping several kilometers of a continuous mono-thread around an evenly spaced circle of 200 aluminum pins. The thread cross, re-cross, and crisscross a circular area above the flat wooden board. The image within the circle is achieved by the painstaking and complex choice of 3800 connections between the pins. After the first 30 connections that make up the image, the number of possible knitting variants exceeds the number of atoms in the Universe! So it’s simply impossible to reproduce this artwork by guesswork or to untangle it with your mind...

title: A Painting About Talking About Paintings
description: I had a blank canvas on the wall and couldn't really think of where to go with it, which is unusual for me. And then I realised that the reason I was distracted was because I was thinking about a video interview I needed to make for an upcoming show in Taiwan. It sort of didn't make sense for me to be talking about the paintings, because the whole point of the paintings is that I'm rubbish at talking so I paint the words instead. So I painted a painting about talking about paintings, which was completely obvious, but took me a while to work out!

author: Heike Roesel
title: Heike Roesel "Solitary Cave", fine art etching in variation, edition of 10
description: ‘Solitary Cave’ is an etchings inspired by anecdotal stories about Jonathan Parson and his lonely mission to save sailors from shipwreck on a stretch of the South Downs coast line, UK, around 1702. He was appointed Curate of St Michael’s church, Litlington in 1692 and later Parson of East Dean, Sussex. Parson discovered natural caverns in the cliffs at Burling Gap and placed lanterns in them to warn approaching ships of the danger of the cliffs. The lights prevented many ships from shipwreck and also helped stranded sailors to exit the beach.

author: Adam Grose MA RWAAN
title: SOMETIMES I SEE PEOPLE
description: This painting takes on the mimesis of a topographical landscape as though seen from above looking down. It takes on the appearance of a rock, a planet, a geological form or the wear and tear of a wall via entropy in the landscape. Inspired by the aesthetics of weathering and aging, the colours and interactions explore a poetical stance through the form of music, in this case listening to Jazz, becoming something more in the imagination of the viewer, as though for the time one looks upon the image, one is transported and transformed. Here, through the elements of nature, we see the reinactment of an object from the landscape - the environmental aspect, the resonances of one form to another, embodying the sublime fascination we have with the environment and the use of material from it to form new objects through the interaction of artistry.

author: Christopher Witchall
title: Heavy Clouds Over Sea
description: Heavy Clouds Over Sea is a realist oil painting on canvas, 12 x 16 inches (approx 30 x 40cm). Inspired by visits to the Suffolk coast town of Aldeburgh, Christopher Witchall continues his preoccupation with the movement and colours of the ocean, a movement frozen in time between the ancient past and an endless future. The artist’s unsentimental approach to his subjects combine two great passions - a love of traditional painting techniques and a fascination with the photographic image. The result of this are paintings that are both painterly and highly realistic. Heavy Clouds Over Sea is painted on a deep edge canvas, so there is no need for framing and can be hung immediately. It is signed on the back and supplied with a signed Certificate of Authenticity.

title: Buddha Love No. 22 - Framed Mixed media art by Kathy Morton Stanion
description: This work of art is a mixed media piece that was created with many layers over time and a lot of experimenting. The process to create these pieces took a long to time to perfect and I believe it to be unique and unlike anything else out there. Each piece takes takes quite a while to create since each individual layer is worked on and must dry before applying the next. Unfortunately there is no way a scan or photograph can capture the true beauty of this piece but I have done the best that I can to show the shimmer and sparkles. This piece actually has silk flowers along with other wonderful things. It is vibrant in color and you can actually look through the layers in this piece.

author: Nicolette Capuano
title: Abstract Landscape Poolside 36x48
description: Washington, DC based artist, Nicolette Capuano, began her career as a mural and decorative artist at the age of 16. Design-centric and dedicated to a lifetime pursuit of creating experiential environments, she launched her abstract art line, Abstract Art Nicolette, with the goal exploring a smaller frame of reference and indulge her creativity in a minimalist direction. Her work is contemporary in aesthetic with graphic design, landscape, and architectural undertones.   Her work seeks to explore balance, harmony, color and texture, and create meditative pieces.

author: Sara Richardson Artist
title: Flirt
description: "Flirt" is a contemporary, nature inspired mixed media piece I have classified as a drawing but has quite a few painterly qualities in terms of texture, heavy application of color and acrylic under painting. I'm just going to be candid, "Flirt" surprised me in the studio as it evolved...I actually did not mean for the work to turn out so rococo adorable and charming. I was working on a rather amped black and white Melodic Minor piece at the same time and you would think the feeling in the black and white work would carry over. Instead, the romantic suggestions in "Flirt" became undeniable. I let the work grow in the direction of...joyous tangled flora and fauna.

author: Steve White
title: Art is Art. Everything Else is everything else.
description: The saying 'Art is art. Everything else is everything else'  was coined by American abstract artist Adolf 'Ad' Reinhardt (1913-1967). Reinhardt, a member of the American Abstract Artists, was an abstract expressionist who wrote and lectured extensively on art and was a major influence on conceptual art, minimal art and monochrome painting. He contended that his infamous 'black' paintings, which comprised black canvasses on which he overlaid many shades of...er.... black, were the last paintings that anyone could paint. He was wrong in this regard, of course, but for committed artists,  and art lovers everywhere his most famous saying holds true.

author: Ole Karako
title: People in City Park
description: I was heading to the city center, to some bustling recreational spot. Near the Golden Gate, there's a small square with a street café where I ordered a Coffee-Tonic and settled on a bench to draw people. The cozy evening rays of the setting sun slid away like snails. People on the benches changed, and only the elderly lingered a little longer, giving me the opportunity to capture them in my sketch. In this ever-changing dynamic, I had to grasp the composition because it was just a moment. A moment of life plucked from the vast ocean of time...

Remaining , while always faithful , to both Pop-Art and Abstractionism, currents of which I have always been a passionate interpreter.

author: Zakhar Shevchuk
title: Great Flood
description: Zakhar Shevchuk's profound artwork 'Great Flood' unravels a captivating narrative that delves into the might of nature amidst human-made constructions, inspired by the tragedy of war and ecological devastation. At first glance, this large oil painting appears fully abstract, but upon closer examination, the viewer uncovers the profound meaning infused into the canvas. Dominated by blue hues that symbolize water, the painting portrays a violent flood unleashed by the destruction of the Nova Kakhovka dam in southern Ukraine during the ongoing Russian invasion. The depicted water's relentless force sweeps through the canvas, turning yellow-grey and terracotta brown as it engulfs the land, accompanied by white elements illustrating the foaming waves.

author: Federico Cortese
title: Motorcycle
description: My grandfather died before I was born. Although I never knew him, the domestic legends that my mother and father told about him helped to create,  in my childhood fantasy, an almost legendary figure. My grandfather was a blacksmith, but in the post-war period of the small Italian rural province, this meant a handyman, and in fact, if necessary he was a plumber, electrician, bricklayer, carpenter. In our country house we had for years and years, the very old and beautiful red motorcycle that he used for work. And I've always imagined him riding that motorcycle, racing from one village to another, to solve problems and rebuild a nation.

title: Menorcan serenity watercolor painting (2022) | Original Hand-painted Art Small Artist | Mediterranean Europe Impressionistic
description: I visited Menorca for 11 days this spring and it was the happiest possible vacation. We were in time when it was not yet very hot or humid, and we were hiking and exploring a lot. The entire island is surrounded with a natural pathway that goes by beaches, caves, cliffs, through forrests, dunes, villages, farms etc. and it's untouched by pollution, factories etc. and mostly even tourism, at least at the time we visited it. The island, its nature and culture are protected by Unesco and left in a serene state and it's probably the happiest I have ever been just walking there and discovering all these amazing villages, beach, caves and their culture.

I applied the same process for this series of paintings « Almendrones » (Cuban american classic cars). I drew and painted American cars of the 50s then I cut them, fragmented to invent, to compose new and improbable models with for only concern the harmony of forms, lines

author: Andrew  Reid Wildman
title: Doorway in Jerusalem
description: A doorway in a quarter of Jerusalem, a place known as Redemption, a place of bright, relentless, all-illuminating light, a light so bright it blinds, and a place of shadow, of corners, alleys, patches of shade. A doorway can symbolise so much. What lies behind is perhaps our choice, known only to us, our projections, the longings of our hearts, our redemption perhaps. This work is rich in light and contrast, both symbolic and realistic. A perfect gift. A wonderful addition to any collection.

author: Maxine Anne  Martin
title: Raku Meets Art Deco
description: Raku meets Art Deco in this unique dream jar ! there will never be another one like this, as is the nature of Raku. The piece has been fired twice to 1,000 C and then whilst still glowing red from the kiln, plunged into a reduction chamber containing combustible materials that we gather from our Cornish hedgerows! we like to keep our 'recipe' secret as we have discovered amazing natural materials that give us outstanding results.

Time is worse than fire, war, windstorm.... causes even more damage, changes and the most interesting thing is that time has a lot of time for it, as much as it wants - it has so much.... Time is also creative, something grows, transforms, lives! It lives, it exists as much as it has the time given to it....

author: Belgin Yucelen
title: Robe with Colours of the Night and Gold Froggings
description: Throughout the Ottoman Empire, black mourning clothes, described by the Sultan Beyazid II as the “colours of the night” were worn to pay last respects to the deceased and to reflect the suffering of the soul. I added narrow bands of fabric called froggings which were commonly used to fasten kaftans. I chose the noble gold thread the use of which was forbidden in 1716 after a significant increase in its employment in fabrics.  Beyazid II ruled as the Sultan of the Ottoman Empire from 1481 to 1512.

author: OXYPOINT
title: "Lemons"
description: Lemons are yellow. Lemons are sour. Lemons are citrus. We all know this, don't we? But what else do you know about lemons? In Europe, lemons brought there from India after the eastern campaigns of Alexander the Great were at first called Indian apples. The history of the origin of lemons is filled with secrets and mysteries. This fruit does not belong to the creation of nature. Lemon is a hybrid, but it is still unknown in what year it was first bred. I really love lemons! The bright and juicy colors of this fruit in the picture fill the entire surrounding space with vitality and joyful mood.

author: Alison Gibbons Watt
title: Under a Blood Orange Sky
description: A bold abstract work on canvas which refers to memory and dream spaces where fiction and reality overlap. A contrasting mix of brightly hued fragments unite in a range of surface paint treatments. Clean edged forms cut elegantly through the nude ground  and are contrasted by tonal washes of pigment where the brush marks leave a visible trace and a history of imprint. Dreams Never End suggests a space in our conscience where reality gives way to illusion and the places in between where fiction and imagination ignite desire.

When my birds appear on canvas they are singing for you not only for me anymore.

author: Paul Stowe
title: Cellini's Perseus and Medusa
description: An original Pencil Drawing depicting Perseus with the Head of Medusa from the bronze sculpture made by Benvenuto Cellini in the period 1545–1554. The sculpture stands upon a square base with bronze relief panels depicting the story of Perseus and Andromeda, similar to a predella on an altarpiece. It is located in the Loggia dei Lanzi of the Piazza della Signoria in Florence, Italy. The second Florentine duke, Duke Cosimo I de' Medici, commissioned the work with specific political connections to the other sculptural works in the piazza. The piece was revealed to the public on 27 April 1554 and tells the mythological story of Perseus beheading Medusa, a hideous woman-faced Gorgon whose hair was turned to snakes and anyone that looked at her was turned to stone.

title: Hold me tight

The relief is mounted on a black structured wooden panel to secure it during transport. This can be used as a carrier, but direct wall mounting is also possible. The total weight is 8.1 kilograms, the size of the background plate is 47x70 cm. Due to the long, careful storage, drying cracks are no longer to be expected. The roko logo (Roland Köpfer) is visibly carved.

Upon learning of the contest, I wanted to take advantage of my participation to mention the situation that Plataforma SOS Tendidos Eléctricas and the Albacete Association of Ornithology (SAO), have been denouncing for years: the electrocution and collision of avifauna in power lines, which causes the death annually of hundreds of thousands of birds, most of them eagles, as a result of the inadequate conditions of power lines in Spain but especially in Albacete. He had to make a work that showed the magnitude of the wingspan in flight, its beauty and that is why the work rests on an outer point, away from the center of gravity, while trying to show the movement and balance of an instant through a figurative synthesis. For its design I used sketches that I still have from when I was a child and belonged to the bird watching group.

author: Andru Fijalkowski
title: The Whisper ( Fossilized Wood )
description: This work was inspired by a whisper that was relaying some important secret. The hand raised, so no one could see the act of betrayal, the hair standing on end, to signify the seriousness, one eye closed, the other eye open,  mouth wide in full flow. This I witnessed and so became part of series of my “ Fossilized Wood “ collection.              I hope the viewer would feel the presence of this work, the subject, the carving and the wonderful medium that is fossilized wood. This is a rare and beautiful material that is found in very few places and it’s colour is natural black, as it has spent thousands of years buried in peat of the Fens, where I was lucky enough to come across it and so I lived amongst it, gathering it from the fields and creating a body of work over many years, that I return to using what wood I have left. To me Bog Oak has a special quality and beauty that I try to reveal.

author: Raúl Lara
title: Vultus Subalbidum
description: This is an experimental series where I seek to deconstruct painting in the same way that a chef does in modern cuisine, transforming the ingredients of a traditional dish into other textures, shapes and temperatures without breaking the flavors and harmonies of the ingredients. I achieve this deconstruction of art by combining the two main concepts of my work, painting and image transfer through photography. What I do first is a classic realistic painting on canvas and photograph it. Then I transfer that photograph printed on paper with gesso to another canvas, which is the final canvas.

author: Manuel Grosso
title: Segnica
description: Walking along a country road that led me to the farmyard of an old disused house, among beautiful elms, I found traces on the ground probably left by metal nets. I was immediately fascinated by their intertwining, they looked like city maps, streets seen from above, and so I decided to detect them by making a cast which then, once brought to the studio, I painted with monochromatic glazes turning towards blue. I therefore wanted to lighten the earth by painting it with the colors of the sky and witness the wonderful unexpected events, if we have attentive eyes like those of children, that a sweet spring walk can offer.

title: SUNNY PEAKS DRAMA
description: Sunny Peaks Drama? This photo was taken on my cross country ski trip in Austran Alpes. The sun was getting down and I knew I had a lot of kilometers yet to go. I was watching the progressive cold shadow and vanishing colorful testemony of the sun on the opposite peaks with fear. That trip ended up as partially night expedition. Luckily it turned out that the combination of the white snow and Moon on the sky gives enough light to find a safe way to my destination. So the fear when taking this photo was more dramatic than the real situation few hours later.

description: Another painting from the archives! This idea is inspired from my time spent at a temple in eastern Thailand. Wat Pananachat is a well known forest monastery, with English as its main working language.  I was fortunate to spend a month there serving the monks, meditating, etc. It also ignited the idea to draw the robes, monks, a theme I still like to come back to every now and again. Here is an early attempt in 3 versions. This is the richly coloured version. There is also a softer version, and a rough in black ink on a textured handmade paper. Each is posted separately.

author: Julie Parker
title: Tangle
description: I am interested in human traces and make sculptures using collected human hair. My two dimensional work is linked to this and gives me space to think about my sculptures and installations. I have developed calligraphic shapes from the way loose hairs lay on surfaces. Sometimes they are shown in small drawings, but they can also be room sized sculptural installations. My drawings and paintings sometimes hint at psychological states, often trying to gain order from disorder, or playing with the fear of the abject.  Tangle is one of these. author: David Lloyd
title: You'll Never Walk Alone 1
description: Ever since I can remember I have been a fan of Liverpool Football Club. It was never a conscious choice, just was how it was growing up in Liverpool with a father and family who loved football and myself playing in teams with my brother from a young age. Some of my earliest memories are watching Liverpool on T.V winning in Europe and the Milk Cup, which shows my age! I was always struck by the passion and creativity of the supporters, making flags and signs to take to the match at home and abroad and singing “You’ll Never Walk Alone” with such enthusiasm. These pieces are inspired by this passion and love shown by the supporters of my hometown football club Liverpool FC and in recognition of the world famous football anthem that never fails to raise emotions.

author: Bart Soutendijk
title: #9930 nude
description: This is a 16 X 30-inch welded wire wall sculpture of a nude female. It is made of 3 mm thick (#12 gauge) low carbon steel wire that I bend by hand and weld in numerous spots to assure stability, then powder coat gloss black** with an extremely durable, weather resistant material that makes it suitable for outdoor installation and wet locations indoors.  The sculpture is easily installed on a wall according to instructions I provide.  It is designed to hang approximately two inches from the wall surface so that it projects a moving shadow. The piece is signed with a thinner wire.

author: Nick Psomiadis
title: Zig Zag Balnarring
description: "Zig Zag Balnarring" is a captivating photograph taken by photographer Nick Psomiadis. A photograph of the Zig Zag groyne at Balnarring Beach in Victoria showcases the rugged coastline and the man-made structures designed to protect it. The groyne’s jagged angles and rough texture contrast against the smooth, rolling waves, creating a striking image that captures the natural beauty and man’s attempts to tame it.

author: Tal Paz-Fridman
title: Sunrise over Ramon crater #6 | Limited Edition Fine Art Print 1 of 10 | 60 x 40 cm
description: The Ramon Crater in Israel’s Negev Desert is the world’s largest erosion crater or makhtesh. A landform unique to Israel’s Negev and Egypt’s Sinai deserts’, a makhtesh is a large erosion cirque, created 220 million years ago when oceans covered the area (the word crater is therefore a misleading translation of Hebrew to English.) The Ramon Crater measures 40km in length and between 2 and 10km in width, shaped like a long heart, and forms Israel’s largest national park, the Ramon Nature Reserve.

description: 500 million birds of different sorts and species stopover at the Hula Valley, in northern Israel, on their flights between Europe and Africa. The main migrating season is in the fall, when pelicans, herons, storks, and cranes arrive in huge flocks, along with birds of prey and other winged species. About 35,000 cranes arrive in the autumn months, and about 15,000 of them stay for the winter.
